headline: How Nvidia's chips became central to the U.S.-China trade war
summary: When Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang revealed Friday that the company is working with the Trump administration on a new computer chip designed for sale to China, it marked the latest chapter in a long-running debate over how the U.S. should compete with China’s technological ambitions.  The reasoning has sometimes changed — with U.S. officials citing national security, human rights or purely economic competition — but the tool has been the same: export controls, or the threat of them.  Nvidia believes it can eventually reap $50 billion from artificial intelligence chip sales in China.

headline: Business Lookahead: Did you say sell tech?
summary: STORY: From Nvidia earnings to political paralysis in Japan, these are the stories to watch in business and finance in the coming week.:: Lookahead:: Nvidia earnings Nvidia's Wednesday earnings report takes on greater significance after tech shares stumbled on some caution over the AI boom.Any commentary from the bellwether related to demand and spending could have broad ramifications for companies exposed to AI. Focus could also fall on Nvidia's deal with the Trump administration, which gives the U.S. government 15% of revenue from sales of some advanced chips in China.:: Global defense stocksGlobal defense stocks took a beating on signs that peace could return to Ukraine.The sector has been on a tear most of 2025 - as conflicts in the Middle East and Ukraine have prompted governments to boost defense spending.But geopolitical analysts caution that it's far too soon to start pricing in a "peace dividend.":: Political paralysisPolitical paralysis in Japan is putting pressure on the bond market, with 10-year bond yields hitting their highest since 2008, and 30-year yields at all-time peaks.Calls continue for Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba to step down, and things could come to a head this week.His ruling Liberal Democratic Party will release a fact-finding report on the reasons for the poor poll showing by month-end.
